Looks like the JavaScript bindings for Tessel are better. Comparing the demo for blinking an LED:<p><pre><code>  var b = require(&#x27;bonescript&#x27;);
  var state = 0;

  b.pinMode(&quot;USR3&quot;, &#x27;out&#x27;);
  setInterval(function() {
    state = state ? 0 : 1;
    b.digitalWrite(&quot;USR3&quot;, state);
  }, 100);
</code></pre>
vs<p><pre><code>  var tessel = require(&#x27;tessel&#x27;)
  tessel.led(1).blink()
</code></pre>
If they can give human-friendly names to stuff like &quot;USR3&quot; and &quot;P9_40&quot; and &quot;P9_36&quot; out of the box, then I&#x27;d say they&#x27;ve added some value.
